	<tr>
		
			<td bgcolor="#DEDACB">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Barbarian Shaman:<BR>
<BR>
There are many advantages and disadvantages to  playing a barbarian shaman over a troll or ogre.  If the other guides haven't convinced you that being a shaman is a top choice, I suggest you try it for a few levels - you'll be sold.<BR>
<BR>
PROS: Halas and Everforst. These are truly superb hunting grounds for levels 1 - 5. Not only are there tons of MOBs, but they carry excellent loot. Gnoll <BR>
pups and Ice goblin whelps often drop backpacks and bags which saves you one decision regarding initial investments. As you will have such good strength you <BR>
can carry a lot more equipment, and therefore make less trips home for selling. There are also some shop<BR>
keepers outside the city so you don't have to zone.<BR>
One of the most impressive things about Everfrost is the variety of players. There are often very high level characters there preparing for a journey into Permafrost, so you can get lots of advice. Another advantage to starting in Halas is the quests. There are literally dozens of them, and some of them give really useful items and gold. For example, I have received five of my spells through questing - always a <BR>
nice gift!. Once you move up to levels 6 and above, it gets  a little more difficult, and having played a lot of<BR>
different class combos, I have to say I think that level 8 for a shaman is harder than any other I have encountered. You simply must group or you will never get to the new rank of spells.<BR>
<BR>
Barbarian buffs are the best. You can buff specifically  without wasting mana, keeping the agility for spellcasters<BR>
and the others for tanks. You can melee blues up to level 8  without any spells if you choose wisely! That plus the fact that shamans get Wolf Spirit at level nine (and not fourteen like druids)<BR>
makes it worth while on it's own.<BR>
<BR>
CON: Despite what I have heard other people say, I have seen an awful lot of Barbarian shamen. In fact, Everforst seems to be overloaded with them, as the only choices for a barbarian are warrior, rogue and shaman. So, if you don't mind others of your class all around, go for it. The other downside to playing a barbarian shaman is night vision. In Everfrost, this handicap cannot be  overestimated. It gets PITCH BLACK at night, and is very easy to get<BR>
lost. God forbid you should die without taking a /loc. However, you o eventually get the spell 'Serpent Sight' which makes life a lot easier.<BR>
<BR>
If you do decide to play a Barbarian Shaman, I would say prepare for three things. A quick start, with good loot and some excellent starting stats. Difficult middle levels which can be soloed but with a lot of difficulty, and finally a great role-play character that becomes more and more enjoyable once you<BR>
surpass the nightmare level 8!<BR>
<BR>
Enjoy!<BR>
<BR>
Mack,<BR>
<BR>
Barbarian Shaman,<BR>
<BR>
Cazic-Thule
